THE AFRICAN DIAMOND MINES. THE Avonderful discoveries of the year 1871, far surpassing in richness everything that had gone before, and proving the South African Diamond Diggings to be no speculative humbug, but a source of great profit, have naturally caused throughout the entire civilized world an all-pervading interest in these mines and a constantly increasing demand for reliable infor mation. Feeling that the trade generally is much interested in these wonderful Fields, we present a short sketch of the events which led to their discovery and subsequent development. "Here be diamonds," appears in large letters on a mission map ofthe southern peninsula of Africa, published in 1750, which conclusively proves that the existence of diamonds in this locality was either known or suspected as early as the middle of the Eighteenth century, yet more than a hundred years elapsed before the events of twenty years ago proved South Africa the richest diamond producing country the world has ever seen. In 1867, a Dutch farmer by the name of Schaik von Nickerk, of the Hope Town Dis- trict of Cape Colony, seeing the children of a neighboring Boer playing with a pretty pebble, was struck by its lustre and weight. He offered to purchase it from Mrs. Jacobs, the mother of the children, but the idea of selling the stone was laughed at by the good woman, and she gave it to him at once, as it was considered of no A*alue. This stone was then sent through a Mr.

O'Reilly to Dr. G. W. Atherstone, an excellent mineralogist of Grahams Town, Avhose opinion of it was requested, as to whether it was of any value. Dr. Atherstone had never seen a rough diamond, he therefore examined it for hardness, specific gravity, polarized light, etc., and pronounced it a genu ine diamond of considerable value, recommending that it be sent to the Paris Exposition (of 1867), which was just about to open, as a great curiosity. This Avas accordingly done, and the stone was purchased after the close of the Exposition by Sir P. E. Woodenhouse, Governor of the Colony, for .£500. The weight was 2 1 carats. Such is the history of the discovery ofthe first " Cape " diamond, Avhich was but the beginning of an industry that has since assumed enormous proportions. In the earlier part of 1870, the number of diamonds found was so con siderable as to attract the attention of the inhabitants of the various colonies of South Africa, which resulted in a "rush" for this district setting in from all quarters, and the banks of the Vaal became in a few months covered with busy diggers. The result was numerous finds of diamonds, the most promi nent of which was the "Star of South Africa," a piece 83 carats in weight, Avhich was sent to England, and produced after cutting a stone of great beauty, weighing 46^ carats, and valued at $100,000. In 1 87 1, in the midst of prosperity along the river, came news ofthe dis covery of diamonds at Du Toit's Pan, in an open plain twenty miles from the river, which transferred almost the entire population to the Dry Diggings, and in a short time 40,000 people had built up a town around this new field. Next the Bulfontine immediately adjoining was discovered, then the De Beers only a mile away, and last, but not least, Kimberly, Avhich of all the diamond diggings stands pre-eminent. In July, 187 1, this fresh discovery was reported at a small hill or "kopje," situated about a mile from De Beers. The locality was known as "Coles berg kopje," but was subsequently called Kimberly, after Earl of Kimberly, the Royal Secretary of State for the Colonies. Compared with Kimberly, all other diamond mines sink into insignificance. It is but a few acres in extent, yet the precious stones have been so lavishly scattered through its rocks that the output has been simply marvellous.

Prom the date os its discovery toiftle end of 1885 it produced $100,000, 000 Avorth of diamonds. Mr. W. H. tiudlestone, in describing this mine, says : "The diamond rock forms an elliptical pipe running through the sur rounding shales, which are known to the miners as the "reef." At the sur face is a layer of three feet of reddish sand, this is followed by fifteen feet of concretionary limestone, which is succeeded by something like thirty feet of "yellow stuff," with much "floating reef," beloAv Avhich the miner comes doAvn upon the blue earth, which js the famous Diamond-rock of South Africa. The 'yellow stuff is only an altered form of blue earth and the so called floating reef is nothing but debris from the neighboring rocks." We present a correct picture of this mine as a frontispiece, which is reproduced from a photograph taken on the spot. The extent of the diamondiferous region it is at present almost impossi ble to say, but as far back as 1870, it was said to be one thousand square miles in area. The geaeral geological features of the Diamond Fields are said to be throughout the whole tract the same. Trap metamorphic and con glomerate rocks run through the whole valley of the Vaal. The surface soil consists of Avater-Avorn pebbles and extends from both banks of the river considerably inland. The impression made upon the mind is, that the whole region has been subjected to a series of successive disturbances. The diamond rock occurs in pipes or pockets in the earth, of considerable depth, which are scattered about over this entire region, and are walled in by slaty rocks which rise to, or nearly to the surface of the ground. Most geologists maintain that these pipes or pockets have been filled by the oozing up from below of the diamond-rock when in more or less of a liquid condition, and it is believed that they are merely the channels that connected ancient volcanic craters Avith deep-seated reservoirs of molten rock. The pockets are staked off into claims, a claim consisting of a plot of ground thirty-one feet square, many of which were sub-divided as the yields became richer, and fabulous sums have been paid for small portions of claims. A cubic yard of earth is said to produce, on the average, $2.00 worth of diamonds. The mining is carried down vertically as far as paying earth is found, a narroAv wall being left standing between each claim. It is evident that the workino* aAvay of the diamond-rock in all directions, and to the very great

depth to which it has been carried, there must be some chance of the side walls of the mines proper and the division walls of the claims unequally Avorked, giving way and falling in upon the mine. Such falls ofthe "reef" have frequently taken place, and one of unusual magnitude occurred in the spring of 1883, which seriously interfered with the workings and overwhelmed many claims. The famous Diamond-rock is of a bluish grey color and a peculiar form ation, having somewhat the appearance and consistency of cement, and may be readily reduced to powder under the blow of a club. Its general charac ter is that of a soft mineral, soapy to the touch. If this rock be thoroughly dried in the sun and then wet with water, it falls to pieces in a crumbly mass, a fact which is put into practical use in separating out the diamonds. In the early days the primitive method of breaking the rock into a fine mass with a wooden mallet was pursued, it was then put on a table and sorted, but by this process many of the smaller diamonds were lost, and it was not until 1874 that the new method was introduced. This consists of raising the blue earth to the surface of the ground in large iron tubs, which run along the wires stretched from the claims — reference to the illustration in front will give an idea how innumerable these wires are ; it is then put on tram cars and run to a drying ground, where it is spread out and dried in the sun. It is afterwards wet and dried again, when it becomes ready for the washing machines. These are circular in shape, somewhat resembling a large pan. From the centre rises an iron rod from which radiate wooden arms having iron teeth pointing downward. By the application of steam power these arms and teeth revolve. The earth enters the machine through a revolving sieve and trough, and a constant stream of water forms a puddle in which the dia monds sink to the bottom, being of great specific gravity. Whatever is found at the bottom of the machine is then sorted and the diamonds, quartz, etc., separated from the pebbles, and after grading for quality, they are ready for the market. Much new and expensive machinery has been introduced of late years and improvements are constantly being made. Some idea of the extent to which the Diamond Mining industry has grown may be obtained from the official figures for the year 1 886, reported by the London and South African Exploration Company, Limited. Accord-

ing to this report the total number of claims in the Kimberly Mine were 345, the greatest depth to which open workings had been carried 400 feet, and underground workings 520 feet. The De Beers, Bulfontine, and Du Toit's Pan mines had an aggregate number of 2798 claims, and an annual production of something like $22,500,000 worth of rough. Since that time all of the above diggings have been consolidated into the famous De Beers Syndicate, which controls nearly the entire diamond out put of South Africa. This syndicate, which Avas formed in 1888 Avith a nominal capital of about $20,000,000., has done much toward giving a stability to the diamond market and placing values upon a fair and equitable basis, from Avhich there is little likelihood of any material fluctuation. In conclusion we Avould say that there is no danger of the diamond ever becoming common. It has been placed by nature in lands difficult of access, and is likely always to remain a royal gem.
